WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:04.510
&gt;&gt; From The Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:04.510 --> 00:00:20.080
[ Pause ]

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:21.970
&gt;&gt; Pamela Jackson:
Wow, this is exciting.

00:00:21.970 --> 00:00:23.470
So good morning.

00:00:23.470 --> 00:00:25.100
I'm Pam Jackson.

00:00:25.100 --> 00:00:28.410
I am the Director for the Library
of Congress Center for the Book,

00:00:28.410 --> 00:00:30.470
and I'd like to welcome
you here this morning,

00:00:30.470 --> 00:00:32.730
and thank you very
much for being here.

00:00:32.730 --> 00:00:34.510
Welcome you to The
Library of Congress

00:00:34.510 --> 00:00:38.070
and to the Coolidge Auditorium,
and I'd like to welcome the staff

00:00:38.070 --> 00:00:42.270
and leadership of the National
Campaign to Stop Violence.

00:00:42.270 --> 00:00:45.530
I'd like to welcome the students,
the parents, the guardians,

00:00:45.530 --> 00:00:49.790
educators, leaders, Department
of Education officials,

00:00:49.790 --> 00:00:53.000
Foundation officials
that support the program,

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:56.670
Do the Write Thing,
Challenge program.

00:00:56.670 --> 00:00:59.770
To my Library of Congress
colleagues I thank you

00:00:59.770 --> 00:01:01.180
for your presence here, as well.

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:03.720
It's an honor to have you all here

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:06.690
and it's a privilege
to be in your midst.

00:01:06.690 --> 00:01:10.130
It's a part of our vision here
at The Library of Congress

00:01:10.130 --> 00:01:14.240
that we are the chief steward of
the record of knowledge for America

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:18.970
and for the world, thus, creating
a springboard to the future.

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:24.700
And the future that I hope to see
is one of compassion and courage,

00:01:24.700 --> 00:01:29.520
one of industry and innovation,
one of remarkable accomplishment

00:01:29.520 --> 00:01:34.020
and achievement, one
of peace and harmony.

00:01:34.020 --> 00:01:37.860
A part of the Library's
central mission is

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:42.950
to provide the American people with
a rich diverse and enduring source

00:01:42.950 --> 00:01:49.810
of knowledge that can be relied
upon to inform, inspire and engage,

00:01:49.810 --> 00:01:53.120
and to support intellectual
and creative endeavors.

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:59.280
The future I want to live in is one
where societies thrive and flourish

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:01.480
because we live in
caring communities,

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:05.520
strong, educated, empowered.

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:08.530
We live as individuals contributing
to one another's intellectual

00:02:08.530 --> 00:02:11.880
and creative endeavors consistent
with the Library's mission,

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:14.840
a future where we care
about each other's success

00:02:14.840 --> 00:02:16.210
and growth and development.

00:02:16.210 --> 00:02:21.680
The future I want is
one in which each of us,

00:02:21.680 --> 00:02:27.360
every one of us values
human life, honors it,

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:30.850
respects it, cherishes it.

00:02:30.850 --> 00:02:35.030
And I'm clear today, we're
here today in this room

00:02:35.030 --> 00:02:40.620
because that future has yet to
be fully and completely realized.

00:02:40.620 --> 00:02:42.280
We're here today in
this room because some

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:46.650
of us have been hurt and harmed.

00:02:46.650 --> 00:02:53.830
Others of us have suffered
and been helpless or silent.

00:02:53.830 --> 00:02:58.790
Still others have been the
source of hate and injury.

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:07.110
It may be you or the person next
to you, but really it's all of us.

00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:10.510
You all, in particular
the authors of the letters

00:03:10.510 --> 00:03:14.850
in this fabulous program and
book, have my deepest appreciation

00:03:14.850 --> 00:03:17.910
for your strength and
for your courage.

00:03:17.910 --> 00:03:22.700
I'm grateful you're here to share
your stories, to add your writings

00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:27.700
to the collections of the
Library and to promote peace.

00:03:27.700 --> 00:03:30.250
The Library of Congress
Center for the Book,

00:03:30.250 --> 00:03:33.310
which does include the Young
Reader Center and the Poetry

00:03:33.310 --> 00:03:37.570
and Literature Center promotes
books and libraries, literacy

00:03:37.570 --> 00:03:40.140
and reading, poetry and literature.

00:03:40.140 --> 00:03:45.750
And we do so because we know
they are the source and the fuel

00:03:45.750 --> 00:03:52.060
for informed and engaged societies
and communities, and we also do

00:03:52.060 --> 00:03:55.750
so because we know they are
the absolute best weapons

00:03:55.750 --> 00:04:00.350
against intolerance
and against ignorance.

00:04:00.350 --> 00:04:05.510
The Center for the Book was
established by Public Law in 1977

00:04:05.510 --> 00:04:08.570 position:56%
and incorporates several
public-private partnerships designed

00:04:08.570 --> 00:04:12.620
to implement programs and awards,
such as this one, and we are part

00:04:12.620 --> 00:04:16.230 position:56%
of the National and International
Outreach Division within The Library

00:04:16.230 --> 00:04:21.030
of Congress so it's our mission
to nurture and empower the network

00:04:21.030 --> 00:04:25.110
of organizations with whom we
partner to strengthen our capacity

00:04:25.110 --> 00:04:29.140
to serve communities and to
provide the broadest access

00:04:29.140 --> 00:04:32.570
to the vast diverse
and rich collections

00:04:32.570 --> 00:04:34.360
of The Library of Congress.

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:37.060 position:56%
We are proud and completely thrilled

00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:39.910
to count the Do the
Write Thing program

00:04:39.910 --> 00:04:43.060
as our partner and our friend.

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:45.980
And it's clear from my
reading of these letters

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:51.920
that we can win the battle against
hate and violence and intolerance

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:56.620
because of who you are, your
willingness to shine brightly

00:04:56.620 --> 00:04:59.280
and be your best self,
and your willingness

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:02.320
to forgive and have compassion.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:07.700
So I'm profoundly convinced that
the future that I said I wanted,

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:10.610
that will be, because
you're here today.

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:12.510
Thank you for being here.

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:23.270
[ Applause ]

00:05:23.270 --> 00:05:27.850
Now please join me in giving a
very warm welcome to Dan Callister,

00:05:27.850 --> 00:05:32.080
Chairman of the National Campaign
to Stop Violence, Chairman

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:33.790
and its Founder I just learned.

00:05:33.790 --> 00:05:35.090
Thank you so much.

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:36.890
Please welcome Dan.

00:05:36.890 --> 00:05:46.800
[ Applause ]

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:48.100 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Dan Callister: Thank you, Pamela.

00:05:48.100 --> 00:05:52.370
It's great that you were
willing to let us come here

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:56.070
and continue our partnership
with the Center for the Book.

00:05:56.070 --> 00:06:00.990
I had no idea how eloquent you
are, a very impressive speech.

00:06:00.990 --> 00:06:05.700
And I would like to say hello
to an old friend up here.

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:08.290
John, would you just
stand up for one minute?

00:06:08.290 --> 00:06:10.510
John has run the Center
for the Book.

00:06:10.510 --> 00:06:16.070
[ Applause ]

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:18.840
